ITU Graphics Programming

Exercise 04 - Textured terrain

Learning objectives

In this exercise we will :

  • Generate textures procedurally and use them in shaders.
  • Load textures from files.
  • Sample textures in vertex and fragment shaders.
  • Mix different textures to get the desired result.
  • Visualize how blending can change the final look of rendered objects.

Remember that you can find hints in comments in the code, tagged with the label "(todo)" followed by the number of the exercise.

References

  • LearnOpenGL - Textures: https://learnopengl.com/Getting-started/Textures
  • Texture library: https://freepbr.com/

Exercise 04.1 - Creating a heightmap to deform the terrain

In this exercise we will improve the terrain of exercise01, adding textures to it.

We will start with a procedural grid, but with no elevation. In Render() you can find a call to DrawObject(), with the terrain mesh, the default material, and a transformation matrix, applying a scale of 10.

The first task is to generate height, again, for the terrain. This time, however, we will store the height in a texture (height map) and sample it from the vertex shader.

  1. Create a new texture, following the same pattern as the default texture, with the same size of the terrain. The format will be FormatR (one channel), and the internal format InternalFormatR16F (one channel, 16 bits, floating point). For the data, see the next step.
  2. Create an array/vector to contain the data of the texture. In this case, the size will be gridX * gridY * 1 float. Use this array to set the image.
  3. Fill in the content of the texture using two nested for loops with the dimensions of the grid. For each pixel, use something simple for now, like std::sin(0.1f * i) * 0.1f, for a wavy pattern.

With the texture created, we need to add it to the shader.

  1. Duplicate the default vertex and fragment shaders, and rename them as terrain.vert and terrain.frag.
  2. Create a new shader program, loading the shaders that you just created. You can copy and paste the code that creates the default shader, but try to understand what it is doing.
  3. Create a new material, using the new shader, and add it to the list of materials.
  4. Change the index of the material in the DrawObject() call for the terrain, in the Render() function, to your new material, number 1. Just for this exercise, it is ok to hardcode these numbers.
  5. Make sure that your code still renders the terrain as before.
  6. Open terrain.vert, and add a new uniform, named Heightmap, of type sampler2D. This will be the texture that we will use to read the height.
  7. In the shader code, read the texture value, using the predefined function texture(), that takes 2 parameters, the sampler and a vector of texture coordinates. For the texture coordinates, we will use the VertexPosition.xz.
  8. In the calculation of the WorldPosition, use the VertexPosition.x, the height, and the VertexPosition.z, instead of the VertexPosition.

Depending on the content of the texture, you should see something different than a plane. If you used the suggested code, you should see some vertical waves.

Now that we know how to read a texture from the vertex shader, we can compute the random height map:

  1. Back to the height map texture generation, replace the placeholder std::sin() with a call to the stb_perlin library. You can use stb_perlin_fbm_noise3 with similar values as in exercise01.
  2. For the coordinates in which to sample the noise function, we can use the indices of the loops, i and j, divided by the (width - 1) and (height - 1) (the minus one is needed for the last vertex to have a value of 1). You can use any value for Z. I will use 0.

If everything went well, you should see a terrain patch similar to the one in exercise01.

Exercise 04.2 - Adding more terrain patches

The advantage of this technique is that you can reuse the same geometry for many different patches, just changing the texture.

In this exercise we are going to create another 3 patches, all with different height maps, forming a square around the origin.

  1. Add 3 new calls to DrawObject, with the terrain mesh and the default material. Use your knowledge about transformation matrices to place them next to each other, forming a square.
  2. Create 3 new materials, copied from the terrain material.
  3. Create 3 new height maps, passing the same dimensions and the coordinates of each patch (0,-1), (-1,0) and (-1, -1).
  4. Use the coordinates to modify the point where the noise function is sampled. Just add them to the X and Y variables, to create different values for each patch, but still connected. For instance, in the case of (0,-1), the Y coordinate will go from -1 to 0, connecting with the original patch that goes from 0 to 1.
  5. Assign the new textures to the new materials, and use these ones in the new calls to DrawObject.

After running the scene, you probably noticed that the patches don't fit perfectly. This is because we are not sampling the texture in the correct place. We need to apply an offset to sample exactly in the middle of each texel.

In the vertex shader, when sampling the texture, use this coordinates: (VertexPosition.xz * 127 + 0.5f)/128 instead of VertexPosition.xz. If you are curious about this, you can ask your teacher for more information.

Exercise 04.3 - Texturing the terrain

Before we start, comment out the line that enables wireframe. You should see now your terrain in solid white.

To add textures to the terrain, we first need to modify the fragment shader:

  1. Add a new uniform, ColorTexture, of type sampler2D, in the terrain fragment shader.
  2. Sample the texture using the texture coordinates (TexCoord), that we are passing from the vertex shader. Set the result as the FragColor, multiplied by the Color uniform.
  3. In the your first terrain material, set the uniform "ColorTexture" to the default texture. Write this line before the other terrain materials are created, so they can benefit from it as well (since they are copies of this one) .

You should see now the default texture, which is a bright magenta color.

The next step is to load texture files. You can choose from the ones in the textures folder, or import your own. We will start with the grass texture in "textures/grass.jpg".

  1. Create a new member variable for the new texture, a shared pointer to a texture 2D.
  2. Find the function LoadTexture(). We will load the textures into the new variable with this function, just using the path and asuming format RGBA8.
  3. In that function, use stbi_load to get the texture data. You can read the documentation in the header file. We will force 4 components.
  4. Observe the SetImage function and make sure you understand all the parameters.
  5. After SetImage, generate the mipmaps for the texture.
  6. Don't forget to use stbi library to free the memory that it allocated (we don't need it after SetImage).
  7. Set this new texture as the ColorTexture of the original terrain material.

We are close... but not finished yet. The texture coordinates are mapped to have one full texture each quad. That is too small, we have to re-scale them.

  1. Create a new uniform ColorTextureScale in the fragment shader, of type vec2.
  2. Use it to multiply the TexCoord in the shader.
  3. Store the value of that property in the original terrain material, use something small, like vec2(0.01).

Exercise 04.3 - Mixing textures depending on the height

In exercise01, we had different colors depending on the height. We can do the same with textures.

  1. Add 3 new textures samplers to the fragment shader.
  2. Create 3 new member variables for the textures, and assign them using the load function. We will use the textures in the exercise04/textures folder.
  3. In the original terrain material, set the uniforms for the new samplers with the value of the new loaded textures.
  4. Add 3 new uniforms to the fragment shader, of type vec2. They will store the height ranges where the textures are mixed. If height is less than the X of the range, it uses the color of the first texture. If it is greater than the Y, it uses the color of the second texture. In between, in interpolates linearly.
  5. In the original terrain material, set the ranges for the new uniforms, making sure that they are in increasing order of height.
  6. Pass the height value from the vertex to the fragment shader.
  7. In the fragment shader code, sample the 4 textures and store the values in local vec4 variables.
  8. Create a function that takes one vec2 range, and one float height. It must return a value between 0 and 1; 0 when height ≤ range.x, 1 when height ≥ range.y, and a linear interpolation for other values of height.
  9. Invoke the function 3 times, and use the return value to mix() each pair of colors.
  10. This exercise is for you to practice some shader coding, but feel free to ask if you don't understand the problem.

Once you have the mixed textures working, tweak the height values until you are happy with the result.

Exercise 04.4 - Water planes

We still have one last job to finalize this nice terrain.

Using the same mesh, we can add 4 patches of water with transparency.

  1. Duplicate the default vertex and fragment shaders, and rename them as water.vert and water.frag.
  2. Add a ColorTexture to the fragment shader, like we did in the terrain shader, multiplying the Color in the output.
  3. You will also need a ColorTextureScale, as in exercise04.2.
  4. Add a new member texture for the water texture, and load the corresponding texture.
  5. Create a new water shader program, and a new water material with it.
  6. Set the uniforms values for the new uniforms.
  7. Add 4 new DrawObject calls, with the same mesh, but all of them using the same water material. For the matrices, you can use the same ones as the terrain patches, but adjusting the Y component to the water level that you want.

The water already looks good like that, but water is usually transparent.

  1. Set the blending equation of the water material to Material::BlendEquation::Add.
  2. Set the blending parameters to alpha blending (check the slides if you don't remember the values).
  3. Set the uniform value of Color to be white but with alpha different than 1. Try different values of opacity.

Congratulations! You have made a full terrain. It is just missing some light, but that will be next week.

Exercise 04.X - Get creative (optional)

There are millions of things to explore with textures and materials, but you can try these;

  • Explore different texture parameters, like the different types of filtering or wrapping.
  • Add basic animation to the water by scrolling the texture coordinates in the water shader.
  • Try different blending modes for the water.
